    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-03-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-03-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="680"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d680">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">867N.01/3–2945: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Roosevelt</persName> to the
                        King of Yemen</hi> (<hi rend="italic">the <persName type="to">Imam Yehya bin
                            Mohamed Hamid-ud-din</persName>
                    </hi>)<note n="54" xml:id="d680fn54">In a telegram dated April 2, 1945, the King
                        acknowledged receipt of the President’s telegram, declaring, “Your high
                        promise and your generous agreement with the rights of Arab peoples and
                        about their sacred places merit the favor and the thanks of all Arabs—nay,
                        of Islam and of all Moslems.” (867N.01/3–2945)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-03-29">March 29,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I have received the telegram which Your Majesty sent me under date of March
                        10<note n="55" xml:id="d680fn55">See footnote 39, <ref target="#pg_692">p.
                            692</ref>.</note> and wish to convey to you my warm appreciation of your
                    expressions of friendship and esteem. The American Government is of course
                    familiar with the views of the Arab States respecting the question of Palestine,
                    and you may rest assured that those views will continue to receive the most
                    careful consideration. I take this opportunity of sending my most sincere
                    greetings to Your Majesty and my best wishes for Your Majesty’s continued good
                    health.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Franklin</hi> D. <hi rend="smallcaps">Roosevelt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
